Regressors Compared:¶

  1. Ridge Regression
  2. Lasso Regression
  3. Elastic Net
  4. SCAD (Smoothly Clipped Absolute Deviation)
  5. Square Root Lasso

In [313]:
def fitModel(model, dataset, ModelName, best = False):
  newmodel = model
  units = ''
  if dataset == "Synthetic":
    XTrain, XTest, YTrain, YTest = synthXTrain, synthXTest, synthYTrain, synthYTest
  elif dataset == "Diabetes":
    XTrain, XTest, YTrain, YTest = diabetesXTrain, diabetesXTest, diabetesYTrain, diabetesYTest
  elif dataset == "Boston Housing":
    XTrain, XTest, YTrain, YTest = bostonXTrain, bostonXTest, bostonYTrain, bostonYTest
    units = "$"
  else:
    print("Incorrect Dataset, try again")
    return
  newmodel.fit(XTrain, YTrain)
  yhat = newmodel.predict(XTest)
  mse = sklearn.metrics.mean_squared_error(YTest, yhat)
  if dataset == "Boston Housing":
      mse = mse*1000
  model_train_score=newmodel.score(XTrain,YTrain)
  model_test_score=newmodel.score(XTest,YTest)
  print("%s R^2 Accuracy on %s dataset:" %(ModelName, dataset))
  print("Train set : %f" %(model_train_score))
  print("Test set: %f" %(model_test_score))
  print("Mean Square Error: %s %.2f" %(units, mse))
  if best == True:
    return newmodel, mse, (model_test_score)
  return newmodel

def printImportances(model, modelName, data_name):
  if data_name == "Synthetic":
    ticks = list(range(0, 6))
    xticks = synth_xticks
  elif data_name == "Diabetes":
    ticks = list(range(0, 10))
    xticks = diabetes_xticks
  elif data_name == "Boston Housing":
    ticks = list(range(0, 12))
    xticks = boston_xticks
  importances = model.coef_
  print(importances)
  for i,v in enumerate(importances):
	  print('Feature: %0d, Score: %.5f' % (i,v))
#  plot feature importance
  plt.bar([x for x in range(len(importances))], importances)
  plt.xticks(ticks, xticks)
  plt.title("%s Regression Variable Importance for %s Dataset" %(modelName, data_name))
  plt.xlabel('Variable Index',fontsize=16)
  plt.ylabel('Coefficient Magnitude',fontsize=16)
  plt.show()

Datasets¶

Boston Housing¶

The Boston Housing Dataset is a dataset of 506 observations and 12 X variables. Each observation represents the average characteristics of a neighborhood or block in Boston, Massachusetts. The y variable that we will try to predict is the Median Price of a house in that neighborhood, in units of $1000.

The X variables for this dataset are described by the data host as -

  1. CRIM - per capita crime rate by town
  2. ZN - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  3. INDUS - proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
  4. CHAS - Charles River dummy variable (1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  5. NOX - nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
  6. RM - average number of rooms per dwelling
  7. AGE - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
  8. DIS - weighted distances to five Boston employment centres
  9. RAD - index of accessibility to radial highways
  10. TAX - full-value property-tax rate per \$10,000
  11. PTRATIO - pupil-teacher ratio by town
  12. B - 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of African-American residents
  13. LSTAT - % of residents considered low-income or impoverished

The dataset appears to have been "censored" at $50,000, with an unusual number of datapoints recording that exact price.

The data will be centered and normalized by Z-score before analysis is begun, to make it appropriate for Ridge and Lasso regressions.

Diabetes¶

The Diabetes dataset represents blood measurements taken from 442 diabetes patients. The dataset has 10 X variables. The y variable is a 'quantitative measure of disease progression.'

The X variables of this dataset represent-

  1. 'age'- age in years

  2. 'sex'- sex of patient

  3. 'bmi'- body mass index of patient

  4. 'bp'- average blood pressure of patient

  5. "s1" - TC, total serum cholesterol

  6. "s2" - LDL, low-density lipoproteins

  7. "s3"- HDL, high-density lipoproteins

  8. "s4" - TCH, total cholesterol / HDL

  9. "s5" - LTG, log of serum triglycerides level

  10. "s6" - GLU, blood sugar level

The data has already been standardized and centered, and will not be further pre-processed before analysis.

Ridge Regression¶

Ridge Regression is a linear least squares regression that uses L2 regularization.

Parameter: Alpha¶

Ridge's alpha parameter controls the strength of the regularization- higher values correspond to a stronger regularization.

We'll demonstrate 3 different Ridge fits, utilizing alpha 1, 10, and 100.

In [230]:
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge

ridgeRegressor1 = Ridge(alpha = 1.0, fit_intercept = False)

ridgeRegressor10 = Ridge(alpha = 10.0, fit_intercept = False)

ridgeRegressor100 = Ridge(alpha = 100, fit_intercept = False)

Ridge - Boston¶

On the Boston dataset, we can see that many variable coefficients are shrunk towards zero. The models with higher alpha settings shrink variable coefficients closer to 0 due to the stronger regression and higher error penalties.

# Of Rooms is the most-predictive variable and is given the highest positive coefficient by all 3 models.

Proximity to noxious industry is given a negative coefficient by most models, suggesting that this is an undesirable trait for homeowners.

The Ridge Regression with alpha = 1 has the lowest Mean Square Error and highest R2 on the test set, and will be compared with the other models in the conclusion of this project.

Lasso Regression¶

Lasso, an acronym for Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator, is a linear regression method that uses the L1 regularization technique.

L1 regularization will force some variable coefficient weights to zero, eliminating them from use in predictions.

Parameter: Alpha¶

Lasso's alpha parameter controls the strength of the L1 regularization.

I demonstrate Lasso regressions using alpha values of 1, 10, and 100.

In [243]:
lasso1 = Lasso(alpha = 1)
lasso10 = Lasso(alpha = 10)
lasso100 = Lasso(alpha = 100)

Lasso - Boston Housing Data¶

The Lasso regressors struggle with the Boston Housing dataset. All three of them have high Mean Square Error and low R2 values.

Both Lasso with alpha 10 and 100 reduce almost all variables to 0, selecting # of Rooms as an important positively correlated variable, and LSTAT (% of residents impoverished( as a negatively correlated variable.

Lasso with alpha = 1 has the highest R2 and lowest MSE, and will be compared to the other regressors in the conclusion.

Elastic Net¶

Elastic Net is another method of linear regression. Where Ridge and Lasso Regressions use L2 and L1 regularizations respectively, the Elastic Net regressor uses a combination of both regularization methods.

L1 Ratio Parameter¶

Elastic Net's L1 Ratio Parameter determines how the regressor combines the L2 and L1 regularization methods. When l1_ratio = 1, the regression is equivalent to a Lasso regression. l1_ratio = 0 corresponds to a Ridge regression. Values between 0 and 1 present combine both regularization methods.

I demonstrate Elastic Net regressors using l1_ratio of 0.2, 0.5, and 0.8

In [256]:
from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet
elastic20 = ElasticNet(alpha=1.0, l1_ratio=0.2)
elastic50 = ElasticNet(alpha = 1.0, l1_ratio = 0.5)
elastic80 = ElasticNet(alpha=1.0, l1_ratio = 0.8)

Elastic Net - Boston Housing Data¶

The Elastic Net regressors all perform similarly well on the Boston Housing Dataset. They all identify # of Rooms as a positively correlated variable, and Lstat and PtRatio as negatively correlated variables.

The Elastic Net with L1 Ratio = 20% has the highest R2 and lowest MSE, and will be compared to other models on this dataset in the conclusion.

SCAD (Smoothly Clipped Absolute Deviation)¶

The SCAD Estimator, proposed by Fan and Li in the above-linked paper, is a modification of Lasso regression. SCAD maintains Lasso's desirable qualities such as handling orthoganal cases and providing continuous solutions, but minimizes some of Lasso's problems when dealing with large regression coefficients.

I use the Pycasso library's SCAD implementation. I won't show any hyperparameter options for this regressor.

SCAD - Boston Housing Data¶

I don't completely understand what's happening here, but I believe this graph shows that SCAD is reducing all variables to a 0 coefficient as the regularization penalty increases.

The model has extremely low R2 and high MSE, so it is performing poorly. Its either a poor fit for the data, or I operated the tool incorrectly.

In [271]:
scadBoston = core.Solver(bostonXTrain, bostonYTrain, family = "sqrtlasso", penalty = 'scad')
scadBoston.train()
scadBoston.plot()

Training is over.
In [272]:
bostonyhat_scad = scadBoston.predict(bostonXTest, lambdidx= 99)
print("%s R^2 Accuracy on %s dataset:" %("SCAD", "Boston Housing"))
bostonSCADmse = sklearn.metrics.mean_squared_error(bostonYTest, bostonyhat_scad) * 1000

Final Comparisons¶

Now that I've compared the regressors' hyperparameters, I'll compare the different regressors accuaracy and variable selection.

I'll create graphs comparing the regressors' importancies and error on each dataset. I'll use the version of each regressor that we had the lowest error on each dataset above.

In [321]:
column_names = ["Model", "Mean Squared Error", "Test R2"]
model_names = ['Ridge', 'Lasso', "Elastic Net"]

Boston Housing Dataset¶

All of the models identified that # of rooms is positively correlated with housing price. Models also identified proximity to the river as being a positive trait, while Distance from Employment Centers, Student/Teacher Ratio, and Portion of Poor Residents (LStat) were all negatively correlated with housing price.

Ridge Regression had the lowest MSE and the best R2 on the test data.

Interestingly, the Square Root Lasso variable selection mirrors the Ridge variable selection, where I expected it to mirror the Lasso selection. I'm not sure if this points to an error in implementing the regressor, or if I misunderstood how the Square Root Lasso functions.

Diabetes Dataset¶

All of the models performed very poorly on the Diabetes datasets.

Their terrible R2 values and high MSE makes me question if examining their variable selections is worthwhile.

Lasso had the highest R2 and lowest MSE.

Three out of four models selected BMI and Blood pressure as having a high correlation with disease progression. S5, one of the blood tests, was also identified as a positive correlation by Ridge, Lasso, and Square Root Lasso.
